,"1120–1200":"1120–1200","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1150–1210":"1150–1210","1152–Male":"1152–Overleden","1154–Male":"1154–Overleden","1080–Male":"1080–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","about 1150":"circa 1150","1080":"1080","1154":"1154","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1150":"1150","Abt 1152":"circa 1152","1115":"1115","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","Abt 1154":"circa 1154","1210":"1210","before 1120":"vóór 1120","about 1200":"circa 1200","about 1120":"circa 1120","Salford, Lancashire, England":"Salford, Lancashire, England","Chorley, Cheshire, England":"Chorley, Cheshire, England","England":"England","Chorley, Macclesfield, Cheshire, England, Britsh Isles":"Chorley, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Macclesfield, Cheshire, England":"Macclesfield, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"about 1120–about 1200":"about 1120–about 1200","1115–Male":"1115–Deceased","1120–1200":"1120–1200","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1150–1210":"1150–1210","1152–Male":"1152–Deceased","1154–Male":"1154–Deceased","1080–Male":"1080–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","about 1150":"about 1150","1080":"1080","1154":"1154","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1150":"1150","Abt 1152":"about 1152","1115":"1115","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","Abt 1154":"about 1154","1210":"1210","before 1120":"before 1120","about 1200":"about 1200","about 1120":"about 1120","Salford, Lancashire, England":"Salford, Lancashire, England","Chorley, Cheshire, England":"Chorley, Cheshire, England","England":"England","Chorley, Macclesfield, Cheshire, England, Britsh Isles":"Chorley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Macclesfield, Cheshire, England":"Macclesfield, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fitton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire):","from Middle English <i>fiton</i>, <i>fittin</i> ‘lie, falsehood’, for a lier or cheat.","possibly a habitational name from Fitton Hall in Leverington, Cambridgeshire, named in Anglo-Scandinavian as ‘settlement by the meadow-land’, from Old English <i>tūn</i> + Old Norse <i>fit</i>, a term denoting grassland on the bank of a river."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard de Fitton was born about 1120, in Macclesfield, Cheshire, England as the son of Hugh de Fitton and Mrs. Hugh de Fitton. He had